1
00:00:54,031 --> 00:00:55,328
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

2
00:00:55,499 --> 00:00:58,332
MAN 1:
Holding. Holding. Ready?

3
00:00:58,502 --> 00:01:02,598
- Yeah, let's go. Up, up, up.
MAN 2: Come on, boys, tackle, tackle.

4
00:01:13,850 --> 00:01:16,842
Good work, boys. Keep it up. Good work.

5
00:01:17,020 --> 00:01:19,454
[CHATTERING]

6
00:01:21,091 --> 00:01:23,616
[SIREN WAILING]

7
00:01:23,794 --> 00:01:26,024
[CAR HORNS HONKING]

8
00:01:28,865 --> 00:01:30,526
[CHEERING]

9
00:01:33,203 --> 00:01:35,330
Mandela! Mandela!

10
00:01:44,648 --> 00:01:48,607
[CHANTING]
Mandela! Mandela! Mandela!

11
00:01:58,428 --> 00:01:59,554
Who is it, sir?

12
00:01:59,730 --> 00:02:02,858
It is that terrorist, Mandela.
They let him out.

13
00:02:03,033 --> 00:02:04,466
Remember this day, boys.

14
00:02:04,635 --> 00:02:07,604
This is the day our country
went to the dogs.

15
00:02:07,771 --> 00:02:10,001
Come. Let's go. Come.

16
00:02:10,173 --> 00:02:14,872
I am now in a position to announce
that Mr. Nelson Mandela will be released...

17
00:02:15,045 --> 00:02:17,240
...at the Victor Verster Prison...

18
00:02:17,414 --> 00:02:21,874
... on Sunday, the 11th of February,
at about 3 p.m.

19
00:02:22,052 --> 00:02:24,646
MAN 1:
There's Mr. Nelson Mandela.

20
00:02:24,821 --> 00:02:26,880
Mr. Mandela, a free man...

21
00:02:27,057 --> 00:02:30,254
... taking his first steps
into a new South Africa.

22
00:02:31,161 --> 00:02:34,255
This is the moment
the world has been waiting for.

23
00:02:34,431 --> 00:02:38,891
MAN 2: And the top news of the day here
in South Africa and around the world.

24
00:02:39,069 --> 00:02:42,061
The recent release
of Nelson Mandela from prison...

25
00:02:42,239 --> 00:02:46,903
... has triggered a power struggle
between the ANC and their black rivals.

26
00:02:47,077 --> 00:02:50,444
There are reports that the government
has been secretly providing arms...

27
00:02:50,614 --> 00:02:52,946
... to these groups,
contributing to the violence...

28
00:02:53,116 --> 00:02:55,676
... that has erupted
throughout the country.

29
00:02:55,852 --> 00:02:59,447
South Africa appears to be
on the verge of a civil war.

30
00:02:59,623 --> 00:03:01,386
MAN 1:
Mr. Mandela has traveled to Durban...

31
00:03:01,558 --> 00:03:06,393
... in an effort to persuade 100,000 angry
young ANC supporters on the frontline...

32
00:03:06,563 --> 00:03:08,121
... to make peace.

33
00:03:08,298 --> 00:03:12,894
Take your knives and your guns
and your pangas...

34
00:03:13,070 --> 00:03:14,970
...and throw them into the sea.

35
00:03:15,138 --> 00:03:17,606
[CHEERING]

36
00:03:18,809 --> 00:03:22,006
MAN 2: After four years of talks,
the day black South Africans...

37
00:03:22,179 --> 00:03:25,012
... have been fighting for
has finally arrived.

38
00:03:25,182 --> 00:03:29,642
For the first time, they are free
to cast their vote alongside whites.

39
00:03:29,820 --> 00:03:32,755
An estimated 23 million people
went to the polls today.

40
00:03:34,124 --> 00:03:38,322
I, Nelson Rolihlahla Mandela...

41
00:03:38,495 --> 00:03:44,957
...do hereby swear to be faithful
to the Republic of South Africa.

42
00:03:45,969 --> 00:03:51,771
Never, never and never again shall it be...

43
00:03:51,942 --> 00:03:55,275
...that this beautiful land will again...

44
00:03:55,445 --> 00:04:00,041
...experience the oppression
of one by another...

45
00:04:00,350 --> 00:04:06,448
...and suffer the indignity
of being the skunk of the world.

46
00:04:11,862 --> 00:04:13,796
Madiba!

47
00:04:16,466 --> 00:04:18,764
Madiba!

48
00:05:01,611 --> 00:05:04,409
Here he is. Like clockwork.

49
00:05:04,581 --> 00:05:06,242
That makes him such an easy target.

50
00:05:18,161 --> 00:05:19,560
Yes, good morning.

51
00:05:19,729 --> 00:05:20,821
[LINGA & JASON SPEAK IN
FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

52
00:05:20,997 --> 00:05:22,225
How are you?

53
00:05:22,399 --> 00:05:25,459
- Us is sharp, Madiba.
- Good.

54
00:05:25,669 --> 00:05:28,604
- Linga, how's your mother?
- She's much better. Thanks.

55
00:05:28,772 --> 00:05:30,569
Good, very good.

56
00:05:33,343 --> 00:05:35,743
[TIRES SCREECHING]

57
00:06:10,747 --> 00:06:12,078
JASON:
Linga, watch your left.

58
00:06:16,152 --> 00:06:19,019
Madiba. Madiba.

59
00:06:29,833 --> 00:06:31,460
It's all right.

60
00:06:35,171 --> 00:06:36,195
What does it say?

61
00:06:37,540 --> 00:06:42,978
It says, "He can win an election,
but can he run a country?"

62
00:06:43,146 --> 00:06:46,377
Not even one day on the job
and they are after you.

63
00:06:46,549 --> 00:06:49,416
It's a legitimate question.

64
00:07:36,866 --> 00:07:39,767
MAN: Today marks the beginning
of a new era in South Africa...

65
00:07:39,936 --> 00:07:43,428
... as President Mandela takes office
in Pretoria.

66
00:07:43,606 --> 00:07:46,803
Facing issues that range from
economic stagnation and unemployment...

67
00:07:46,977 --> 00:07:49,138
... to rising crime,
while at the same time...

68
00:07:49,312 --> 00:07:53,806
... balancing black aspirations
with white fears.

69
00:07:54,617 --> 00:07:58,075
I never thought I'd see the day.
I feel sorry for you, son.

70
00:07:58,254 --> 00:08:01,314
You got your whole life ahead of you.
What's it gonna be like now?

71
00:08:01,491 --> 00:08:02,685
- Don't be so gloomy.
- Yeah.

72
00:08:02,859 --> 00:08:06,226
Now, I added vitamins.
There's a horrible flu bug going around.

73
00:08:06,396 --> 00:08:09,797
- You tell Nerine when you get home, eh?
- Thanks, Mom.

74
00:08:09,966 --> 00:08:11,593
Now, I'm telling you, Frangois.

75
00:08:12,102 --> 00:08:14,866
Look at Angola, look at Mozambique,
look at Zimbabwe.

76
00:08:15,038 --> 00:08:16,300
We're next.

77
00:08:16,473 --> 00:08:19,601
They're gonna take our jobs
and they're gonna drive us into the sea.

78
00:08:19,776 --> 00:08:21,266
Just you wait.

79
00:08:38,828 --> 00:08:40,455
Good morning.

80
00:08:51,908 --> 00:08:53,205
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

81
00:08:53,376 --> 00:08:55,674
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

82
00:08:56,513 --> 00:08:58,538
- Good morning, everyone.
MAN: Good morning.

83
00:08:58,782 --> 00:09:01,376
Brenda, you've had your hair done.
I like it.

84
00:09:01,551 --> 00:09:02,575
Thank you, Madiba.

85
00:09:02,752 --> 00:09:06,119
Yeah, we need to talk about
your cabinet appointments and ministers.

86
00:09:06,289 --> 00:09:08,189
- Give me one moment, please.
- Yes, Madiba.

87
00:09:08,358 --> 00:09:11,122
- After you, Comrade President.
- Thank you, sir.

88
00:09:16,900 --> 00:09:19,334
[PHONE RINGS]

89
00:09:19,502 --> 00:09:21,766
WOMAN:
Office of the president, good morning.

90
00:09:23,473 --> 00:09:24,963
Brenda.

91
00:09:25,542 --> 00:09:29,876
Please assemble all the staff for me.
All those who haven't already left.

92
00:09:30,046 --> 00:09:31,809
Right now? All of them?

93
00:09:31,981 --> 00:09:35,007
- Yes, please.
- Yes, Madiba.

94
00:09:35,885 --> 00:09:39,480
Ladies and gentlemen,
if you would like to follow me, please.

95
00:09:39,656 --> 00:09:42,557
The president would like
to speak with you.

96
00:09:48,832 --> 00:09:50,459
- Here he comes.
- Yeah.

97
00:09:50,633 --> 00:09:53,568
He wants the satisfaction
of firing us himself.

98
00:09:53,903 --> 00:09:56,497
- I'd like you to stay out here.
- Yes, but, Madiba...

99
00:09:56,673 --> 00:09:59,972
I cannot talk to them
hiding behind men with guns.

100
00:10:01,478 --> 00:10:03,673
[MANDELA SPEAKS IN AFRIKAANS]

101
00:10:03,847 --> 00:10:05,405
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

102
00:10:05,582 --> 00:10:06,708
Good morning.

103
00:10:06,883 --> 00:10:08,748
- How are you this morning?
- Fine.

104
00:10:08,918 --> 00:10:10,943
It's good to see you.

105
00:10:11,254 --> 00:10:14,587
Thank you for coming
on such short notice.

106
00:10:15,158 --> 00:10:17,649
Some of you may know who I am.

107
00:10:18,728 --> 00:10:24,564
I could not help
noticing the empty offices...

108
00:10:24,734 --> 00:10:26,929
...as I came to work this morning...

109
00:10:27,103 --> 00:10:29,833
...and all of the packing boxes.

110
00:10:30,607 --> 00:10:35,510
Now, of course, if you want to leave,
that is your right.

111
00:10:35,678 --> 00:10:42,174
And if you feel in your heart that you
cannot work with your new government...

112
00:10:42,352 --> 00:10:44,320
...then it is better that you do leave.

113
00:10:44,487 --> 00:10:46,512
Right away.

114
00:10:46,689 --> 00:10:49,783
But if you are packing up
because you fear...

115
00:10:49,959 --> 00:10:55,454
...that your language
or the color of your skin...

116
00:10:55,798 --> 00:11:00,633
...or who you worked for before
disqualifies you from working here...

117
00:11:00,803 --> 00:11:05,502
...I am here to tell you,
have no such fear.

118
00:11:06,009 --> 00:11:07,567
What is verby is verby.

119
00:11:08,478 --> 00:11:11,174
The past is the past.

120
00:11:11,347 --> 00:11:13,645
We look to the future now.

121
00:11:14,584 --> 00:11:16,381
We need your help.

122
00:11:16,553 --> 00:11:18,817
We want your help.

123
00:11:19,856 --> 00:11:22,290
If you would like to stay...

124
00:11:22,458 --> 00:11:26,986
...you would be doing
your country a great service.

125
00:11:27,730 --> 00:11:33,498
All I ask is that you do your work
to the best of your abilities...

126
00:11:33,670 --> 00:11:35,934
...and with good heart.

127
00:11:36,105 --> 00:11:38,096
I promise to do the same.

128
00:11:39,209 --> 00:11:45,273
If we can manage that, our country
will be a shining light in the world.

129
00:11:54,691 --> 00:11:56,090
Thank you.

130
00:11:56,259 --> 00:11:57,886
[SPEAKS IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

131
00:11:58,061 --> 00:12:00,086
- Is it still morning?
- Yeah.

132
00:12:00,263 --> 00:12:02,163
When you get a chance,
can we get the schedule for the month?

133
00:12:02,332 --> 00:12:03,356
[PHONE RINGS]

134
00:12:03,533 --> 00:12:06,331
- Yeah.
- We need to plan security.

135
00:12:06,803 --> 00:12:09,033
Office of the president, good morning.

136
00:12:09,205 --> 00:12:12,140
Yes, sir.
Will do, we'll have that ready for you.

137
00:12:17,080 --> 00:12:19,048
We need more men.

138
00:12:19,649 --> 00:12:21,344
Did you talk to Brenda about it?

139
00:12:21,517 --> 00:12:23,917
Yes. Yesterday.

140
00:12:24,087 --> 00:12:25,520
[KNOCKING]

141
00:12:25,688 --> 00:12:28,156
Ah. That must be Jessie
with the schedule.

142
00:12:28,324 --> 00:12:29,552
Come in, beautiful.

143
00:12:33,696 --> 00:12:35,357
What's this?

144
00:12:35,531 --> 00:12:36,964
Mr. Jason Tshabalala?

145
00:12:37,400 --> 00:12:39,630
That's me. Am I under arrest?

146
00:12:39,969 --> 00:12:43,461
Captain Feyder and team,
reporting for duty, sir.

147
00:12:44,307 --> 00:12:45,740
What duty?

148
00:12:45,908 --> 00:12:50,106
We're the presidential bodyguard.
We've been assigned to this office.

149
00:12:50,480 --> 00:12:52,277
Here are our orders.

150
00:12:55,218 --> 00:12:57,413
You're Special Branch, right?

151
00:12:58,154 --> 00:13:00,384
You'll see that they've been signed.

152
00:13:00,556 --> 00:13:02,387
Well, I don't care if they are signed...

153
00:13:08,264 --> 00:13:09,754
Just wait here.

154
00:13:25,481 --> 00:13:27,540
Sorry to disturb you, sir.

155
00:13:27,717 --> 00:13:29,480
You look agitated, Jason.

156
00:13:29,652 --> 00:13:32,553
That's because there are four
Special Branch cops in my office.

157
00:13:32,722 --> 00:13:35,555
- Oh, what did you do?
- Nothing.

158
00:13:35,725 --> 00:13:39,786
They say they are presidential bodyguards
and they have orders signed by you.

159
00:13:41,664 --> 00:13:46,192
Ah, yes. Ah, yes. Well, these men
are special trained by SAS.

160
00:13:46,569 --> 00:13:49,629
They have lots of experience.
They protected de Klerk.

161
00:13:49,806 --> 00:13:53,640
- Yes, but it doesn't mean that they have to...
- You asked for more men, didn't you?

162
00:13:53,810 --> 00:13:56,370
- Yes, sir, I asked...
- When people see me in public...

163
00:13:56,546 --> 00:13:58,741
...they see my bodyguards.

164
00:13:58,915 --> 00:14:02,009
You represent me directly.

165
00:14:02,518 --> 00:14:05,487
The rainbow nation starts here.

166
00:14:05,788 --> 00:14:10,054
- Reconciliation starts here.
- Reconciliation, sir?

167
00:14:10,393 --> 00:14:12,953
Yes, reconciliation, Jason.

168
00:14:13,129 --> 00:14:16,394
Comrade President, not long ago,
these guys tried to kill us.

169
00:14:16,566 --> 00:14:19,626
Maybe even these four guys
in my office tried and often succeeded.

170
00:14:19,802 --> 00:14:21,064
Yes, I know.

171
00:14:22,238 --> 00:14:23,933
Forgiveness starts here too.

172
00:14:25,108 --> 00:14:27,235
Forgiveness liberates the soul.

173
00:14:27,777 --> 00:14:33,579
It removes fear.
That is why it is such a powerful weapon.

174
00:14:35,318 --> 00:14:39,118
Please, Jason. Try.

175
00:14:42,091 --> 00:14:44,491
Sorry to disturb you, sir.

176
00:14:51,033 --> 00:14:52,295
Just a minute.

177
00:14:52,869 --> 00:14:54,302
Two copies of the schedule.

178
00:14:55,772 --> 00:14:56,796
Thank you, Jessie.

179
00:15:07,450 --> 00:15:10,544
Jason, can we get rid of these guys now?

180
00:15:14,757 --> 00:15:16,782
This is the schedule for the month.

181
00:15:18,194 --> 00:15:20,526
Let's look them over for assignments.

182
00:15:20,696 --> 00:15:22,755
- Right.
- What?

183
00:15:25,101 --> 00:15:28,935
LINGA:
Hey, Jason. I need to talk to you.

184
00:15:38,481 --> 00:15:39,743
How can we trust them?

185
00:15:39,916 --> 00:15:44,046
We can't. That's what Madiba wants, okay?
Let's go.

186
00:15:47,323 --> 00:15:49,382
Are there any special orders
or conditions?

187
00:15:50,193 --> 00:15:52,718
No. Oh, yes.

188
00:15:52,895 --> 00:15:57,059
Madiba doesn't like it if you don't
smile when you push people away.

189
00:15:57,233 --> 00:15:58,257
Seriously?

190
00:15:58,801 --> 00:16:02,897
Yes, seriously. It's the new South Africa.

191
00:16:03,706 --> 00:16:05,503
Madiba?

192
00:16:05,842 --> 00:16:08,174
That's the president's clan name.

193
00:16:08,344 --> 00:16:10,608
That's what we call him.

194
00:16:11,647 --> 00:16:14,172
We'll call him Mr. President.

195
00:16:15,084 --> 00:16:18,053
Can we go through the schedule now?

196
00:16:18,221 --> 00:16:20,712
Can you gentlemen come closer?

197
00:16:25,161 --> 00:16:27,493
[CHATTERING]

198
00:16:32,468 --> 00:16:36,131
How's he going to do all this?
When does he take a break?

199
00:16:36,305 --> 00:16:38,899
He says he rested enough in prison.

200
00:16:40,276 --> 00:16:42,870
- Here's a headache.
- What?

201
00:16:44,080 --> 00:16:45,945
The rugby match.

202
00:16:46,148 --> 00:16:50,107
England against Springboks,
Loftus Stadium.

203
00:16:50,286 --> 00:16:53,915
Gonna be a headache for England,
that's for sure. We're gonna donner them.

204
00:16:54,090 --> 00:16:56,820
I don't care about the game.
All I care about...

205
00:16:56,993 --> 00:17:00,258
...is that the president will be exposed.
- To a thousand drunken boys.

206
00:17:00,429 --> 00:17:02,420
Sports fans?

207
00:17:02,598 --> 00:17:06,056
Yes. Sports fans.

208
00:17:06,235 --> 00:17:10,171
Who didn't vote for him.
Who probably hate him.

209
00:17:10,339 --> 00:17:13,900
Who came out of the womb with guns
in their hands.

210
00:17:17,280 --> 00:17:18,941
What?

211
00:17:25,087 --> 00:17:28,147
ANNOUNCER:
Let's welcome captain Frangois Pienaar...

212
00:17:28,324 --> 00:17:32,727
...and the South African Springboks
here in Pretoria.

213
00:17:32,895 --> 00:17:37,992
Today's referee is Colin Hawke
from New Zealand.

214
00:17:43,606 --> 00:17:46,939
CROWD [CHANTING]:
Bokke! Bokke! Bokke!

215
00:17:49,879 --> 00:17:51,278
Okay, guys.

216
00:17:51,447 --> 00:17:55,440
I want your eyes on the crowd at all times.
You're staying in the middle of the field.

217
00:17:55,618 --> 00:17:58,781
You're gonna walk in, shake hands,
and walk back and that's it.

218
00:17:58,955 --> 00:18:00,513
- You got it?
- Yup.

219
00:18:00,690 --> 00:18:02,453
Okay, let's go.

220
00:18:17,540 --> 00:18:22,136
ANNOUNCER: Ladies and gentlemen,
it is our pleasure to have with us today...

221
00:18:22,345 --> 00:18:26,372
...at Loftus Versfeld,
our newly elected president...

222
00:18:26,782 --> 00:18:30,445
...Mr. Nelson Mandela.

223
00:18:30,620 --> 00:18:35,489
[CROWD CHEERING AND BOOING]

224
00:18:40,596 --> 00:18:42,587
MAN:
Mandela!

225
00:18:45,835 --> 00:18:48,565
Well, good luck, captain.

226
00:18:49,171 --> 00:18:52,368
Thank you, Mr. President. Thank you.

227
00:18:52,742 --> 00:18:54,937
- Good luck, son.
- Thank you very much.

228
00:18:55,111 --> 00:18:56,976
- Good luck.
- Thank you.

229
00:18:59,281 --> 00:19:01,545
- Good luck, Chester.
- Yes, sir.

230
00:19:01,717 --> 00:19:03,582
- Good luck.
- Thank you.

231
00:19:05,187 --> 00:19:06,677
Sir.

232
00:19:37,253 --> 00:19:39,813
- Stop him.
JASON: No, stay with him.

233
00:19:47,463 --> 00:19:51,229
- Thank you for honoring our new flag.
- It's a pleasure, sir.

234
00:19:51,400 --> 00:19:52,765
Thank you.

235
00:19:52,935 --> 00:19:54,459
How are you? How are you?

236
00:19:54,637 --> 00:19:57,299
- Good to see you. Good to see you.
- Thank you. Thank you.

237
00:19:58,140 --> 00:19:59,505
- Madiba.
- Hi.

238
00:19:59,675 --> 00:20:02,838
Madiba? Madiba?
We're delaying the rugby, sir.

239
00:20:03,012 --> 00:20:05,480
Oh, yes. Oh, yes, of course.

240
00:20:18,160 --> 00:20:20,993
- Why didn't you stop him?
- Well, you try next time.

241
00:20:21,163 --> 00:20:24,530
- Does he do that sort of thing all the time?
- Ask my ulcers.

242
00:20:24,700 --> 00:20:28,101
- Good thing it was just a cup.
ETIENNE: And good thing he never saw it.

243
00:20:28,270 --> 00:20:30,500
JASON:
Oh, he saw it. He sees everything.

244
00:20:30,673 --> 00:20:32,766
I hate rugby.

245
00:20:33,042 --> 00:20:34,066
Engage!

246
00:20:34,243 --> 00:20:35,870
[GRUNTING]

247
00:20:46,789 --> 00:20:48,757
MAN 1: With you, with you!
MAN 2: Here, onside, onside!

248
00:20:48,924 --> 00:20:50,619
Come on! Now, now, now!

249
00:20:57,500 --> 00:20:58,489
ANNOUNCER:
Try, England.

250
00:20:58,667 --> 00:21:02,660
For England, scored by Ben Clarke,
Number 13.

251
00:21:03,139 --> 00:21:06,870
England, 11, South Africa, 0.

252
00:21:07,543 --> 00:21:08,567
Fuck, man.

253
00:21:08,744 --> 00:21:10,405
[SPEAKS IN AFRIKAANS]

254
00:21:10,579 --> 00:21:14,174
These okes mean business.
We need to focus.

255
00:21:14,550 --> 00:21:16,541
Come, okes, we need to focus, focus!

256
00:21:16,719 --> 00:21:17,777
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

257
00:21:17,953 --> 00:21:21,081
MAN: Let's go, boys.
- Right, come on.

258
00:21:30,900 --> 00:21:32,527
ANNOUNCER:
Conversion is good.

259
00:21:32,701 --> 00:21:35,226
Why don't we do a little work
while we watch?

260
00:21:35,404 --> 00:21:39,204
- We have a lot of promises to keep.
- Yes, we do.

261
00:21:45,181 --> 00:21:49,811
Well, it's not too late,
if the boys can just pick up their game.

262
00:21:49,985 --> 00:21:51,612
If they don't, heads will roll.

263
00:21:55,257 --> 00:21:57,725
Come on, you bloody bastards.

264
00:22:06,569 --> 00:22:09,060
Where do you want to go first
for foreign investment?

265
00:22:09,238 --> 00:22:10,705
Where the money is.

266
00:22:10,873 --> 00:22:14,969
America, England, Saudi Arabia.

267
00:22:20,416 --> 00:22:22,884
How long before the World Cup?

268
00:22:23,285 --> 00:22:25,048
About a year.

269
00:22:26,255 --> 00:22:29,588
Well, it's time enough for improvement.

270
00:22:30,025 --> 00:22:32,118
Mr. President.

271
00:22:32,661 --> 00:22:34,822
Don't get your hopes up.

272
00:22:35,164 --> 00:22:37,655
We're a damn disgrace.

273
00:22:39,168 --> 00:22:42,501
ANNOUNCER:
England, 24, South Africa, 9.

274
00:22:42,671 --> 00:22:45,333
Do you see all those old apartheid flags?

275
00:22:45,507 --> 00:22:47,839
- Hm.
- They're a disgrace.

276
00:22:48,010 --> 00:22:49,841
It is also a constitutional right.

277
00:22:50,946 --> 00:22:54,074
Along with the apartheid anthem, I know.

278
00:22:54,250 --> 00:22:57,117
But it's time people moved on.

279
00:22:59,822 --> 00:23:01,517
Look at this.

280
00:23:02,291 --> 00:23:06,193
All of the whites are cheering
for the Springboks.

281
00:23:06,528 --> 00:23:08,758
All of the blacks are cheering
for England.

282
00:23:12,801 --> 00:23:15,201
We used to do that on the island,
you know.

283
00:23:15,371 --> 00:23:18,568
We would cheer for anyone but the Boks.

284
00:23:18,941 --> 00:23:21,432
It made the warders very angry.

285
00:23:21,610 --> 00:23:23,475
Of course it did.

286
00:23:27,016 --> 00:23:29,211
- Sorry I'm late. How is it going?
ANNOUNCER: Number 10.

287
00:23:29,385 --> 00:23:31,182
Very badly.

288
00:23:35,958 --> 00:23:38,188
Maybe it's just as well.

289
00:23:38,560 --> 00:23:40,050
Why?

290
00:23:41,664 --> 00:23:45,532
I've just been at a meeting
of the National Sports executive.

291
00:23:47,503 --> 00:23:52,167
There's a strong support to drop the
Springbok emblem and colors altogether.

292
00:23:52,341 --> 00:23:58,337
If they play badly,
maybe it's a good time to make a change.

293
00:23:58,514 --> 00:24:02,746
This could be the last time
we have to look at the green and gold.

294
00:24:21,036 --> 00:24:24,437
Fuck, man. This is bullshit.

295
00:24:41,590 --> 00:24:45,788
MAN: Frangois Pienaar's team came
to Loftus Versfeld Stadium this afternoon...

296
00:24:45,961 --> 00:24:49,055
... unprepared and arrogant.

297
00:24:49,231 --> 00:24:50,994
They left 80 minutes later...

298
00:24:51,166 --> 00:24:54,795
...with their tails between their legs
like whipped mongrels.

299
00:24:54,970 --> 00:24:57,598
And I, for one, am glad.

300
00:24:57,773 --> 00:25:01,903
Not because they lost,
but because there is now no way...

301
00:25:02,077 --> 00:25:06,070
...to ignore the fact that we are
completely and utterly unprepared...

302
00:25:06,248 --> 00:25:10,708
... to reenter the world
of topnotch international rugby.

303
00:25:10,886 --> 00:25:14,253
The Rugby World Cup
is now less than a year away.

304
00:25:14,423 --> 00:25:17,256
And I, for one, am relieved
that we are the host nation...

305
00:25:17,426 --> 00:25:20,088
... and therefore qualify automatically
for the tournament.

306
00:25:20,262 --> 00:25:22,662
- Somebody gets the ax.
- Because I am not sure...

307
00:25:22,831 --> 00:25:27,097
...that we would get in on merit alone.
- Who's it gonna be?

308
00:25:27,269 --> 00:25:30,329
Pienaar's team played
without discipline...

309
00:25:30,506 --> 00:25:34,306
... without strategy and without courage.

310
00:25:34,877 --> 00:25:37,402
- And therefore...
- He's trying to get them to drop me.

311
00:25:37,579 --> 00:25:41,106
He's just bitter because the Springboks
were boycotted when he played.

312
00:25:41,283 --> 00:25:44,650
Maybe. But people listen
to what he says.

313
00:25:44,953 --> 00:25:47,319
They brought shame upon our nation.

314
00:25:47,489 --> 00:25:51,516
And I, for one, can say
without fear of contradiction...

315
00:25:51,693 --> 00:25:53,251
... that today, these 15...

316
00:25:55,097 --> 00:26:01,434
... so-called men did not deserve
to wear the hallowed green and gold.

317
00:26:04,039 --> 00:26:07,634
Here's your muti, Madiba.
I warmed the milk tonight.

318
00:26:07,810 --> 00:26:11,177
Ah. You are too good to me, Mary.

319
00:26:11,947 --> 00:26:16,213
Your daughter called
to cancel her visit this weekend.

320
00:26:17,953 --> 00:26:19,443
Did she say why?

321
00:26:19,621 --> 00:26:22,454
No, she didn't.
She said to tell you she was sorry.

322
00:26:23,625 --> 00:26:25,183
I see.

323
00:26:27,129 --> 00:26:28,858
Do you need anything else tonight?

324
00:26:30,065 --> 00:26:32,192
No, Mary, thank you. I will go to bed.

325
00:26:32,968 --> 00:26:34,526
Good evening, Dada.

326
00:26:34,903 --> 00:26:36,928
Good evening, Mary.

327
00:27:02,998 --> 00:27:05,159
- Hello. There you go.
DLAMINl: God bless you.

328
00:27:05,334 --> 00:27:07,097
Thank you.

329
00:27:07,269 --> 00:27:10,966
COLE: Some nice pants for you.
DLAMINl: God bless you.

330
00:27:11,740 --> 00:27:13,571
COLE:
There you go.

331
00:27:14,009 --> 00:27:15,909
There you go.

332
00:27:16,078 --> 00:27:18,342
DLAMINl:
God bless you.

333
00:27:22,551 --> 00:27:27,454
You're a very lucky boy.
It's a real Springbok practice jersey.

334
00:27:28,557 --> 00:27:32,186
I mean, I know it's a bit big,
but it's warm and it'll last forever.

335
00:27:32,361 --> 00:27:34,090
Huh? Come.

336
00:27:34,263 --> 00:27:36,754
Go on, take it, it's yours.

337
00:27:39,067 --> 00:27:43,060
- Why won't he take it?
- Lf he wears it, the others will beat him up.

338
00:27:43,438 --> 00:27:45,429
Because the Springboks
are playing so badly?

339
00:27:45,607 --> 00:27:50,203
No, because for them
Springbok still represents apartheid.

340
00:27:57,953 --> 00:28:01,719
And now for the next item on our agenda.

341
00:28:02,057 --> 00:28:07,017
The NSC executive proposes a vote
on the following motion:

342
00:28:07,196 --> 00:28:11,030
That, as a permanent symbol
of the apartheid era...

343
00:28:11,200 --> 00:28:14,260
...the colors, emblem...

344
00:28:14,436 --> 00:28:20,568
...and the name of the Springboks,
be eliminated immediately.

345
00:28:22,611 --> 00:28:27,241
And that all sports teams
representing South Africa...

346
00:28:27,649 --> 00:28:30,982
...shall be known forthwith...

347
00:28:31,653 --> 00:28:34,144
...as the Proteas.

348
00:28:34,323 --> 00:28:38,225
Now, comrades,
we will submit this motion to a hand vote.

349
00:28:38,393 --> 00:28:44,161
And in the event of a close count,
we'll go to a written ballot.

350
00:28:44,333 --> 00:28:49,464
All of those in favor of eliminating
the Springboks, raise your hands.

351
00:28:52,174 --> 00:28:54,938
- Viva, Proteas, viva!
- Viva!

352
00:28:55,110 --> 00:28:57,840
- Viva, Proteas, viva!
- Viva!

353
00:28:58,013 --> 00:29:01,176
- Viva, Proteas, viva!
- Viva!

354
00:29:10,158 --> 00:29:12,353
Both units to their cars right now.

355
00:29:12,527 --> 00:29:14,995
All right, let's go. Let's do it.

356
00:29:20,602 --> 00:29:23,127
BRENDA: What do I tell
the Japanese trade delegation?

357
00:29:23,305 --> 00:29:24,897
MANDELA:
I delegate that decision to you.

358
00:29:25,073 --> 00:29:27,303
- Do you want me to inform the VP?
- No.

359
00:29:27,476 --> 00:29:29,740
We should at least include
the minister of sport.

360
00:29:29,911 --> 00:29:30,935
No.

361
00:29:31,113 --> 00:29:34,344
I strongly advise against doing this,
especially on your own.

362
00:29:34,516 --> 00:29:37,007
It gives the impression
of autocratic leadership.

363
00:29:37,185 --> 00:29:40,621
You risk alienating your cabinet
and your party.

364
00:29:40,789 --> 00:29:42,313
Your advice is duly noted.

365
00:29:42,491 --> 00:29:46,325
Madiba. The people want this.
They hate the Springboks.

366
00:29:46,495 --> 00:29:49,658
They don't want to be represented
by a team they cheered against.

367
00:29:49,831 --> 00:29:52,527
Yes, I know. But in this instance,
the people are wrong.

368
00:29:52,701 --> 00:29:56,262
And as their elected leader,
it is my job to show them that.

369
00:29:56,438 --> 00:29:58,702
You're risking your political capital.

370
00:29:58,874 --> 00:30:01,001
You're risking your future as our leader.

371
00:30:01,176 --> 00:30:05,112
The day I am afraid to do that
is the day I am no longer fit to lead.

372
00:30:08,550 --> 00:30:12,816
At least risk it for something
more important than rugby.

373
00:30:12,988 --> 00:30:16,549
Tell the boys I want to go
to Eersterust, very fast.

374
00:30:19,428 --> 00:30:22,556
[SIREN WAILING]

375
00:30:29,504 --> 00:30:34,441
We, the executive, would like
to applaud you for your diligence...

376
00:30:35,010 --> 00:30:37,137
...and your courage.

377
00:30:43,685 --> 00:30:47,086
Please join us in our anthem.

378
00:30:55,597 --> 00:30:59,658
[SINGING IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

379
00:31:14,716 --> 00:31:17,150
Comrades, comrades,
members of the choir.

380
00:31:17,319 --> 00:31:22,882
We would only interrupt such beautiful
music for something truly important.

381
00:31:23,058 --> 00:31:27,188
Please, welcome President Mandela.

382
00:31:32,100 --> 00:31:33,465
Thank you.

383
00:31:34,069 --> 00:31:36,765
WOMAN: Madiba.
MAN 1: Welcome, Madiba.

384
00:31:36,938 --> 00:31:39,498
- Thank you.
MAN 2: Mandela.

385
00:31:41,676 --> 00:31:45,009
- Mandela.
- Thank you.

386
00:31:49,418 --> 00:31:51,852
I thank you. Please.

387
00:31:53,321 --> 00:31:54,345
Smile.

388
00:31:59,227 --> 00:32:00,819
Brothers...

389
00:32:01,763 --> 00:32:03,230
...sisters...

390
00:32:03,765 --> 00:32:05,665
...comrades.

391
00:32:06,868 --> 00:32:11,862
I am here because
I believe you have made a decision...

392
00:32:12,040 --> 00:32:17,535
...with insufficient information
and foresight.

393
00:32:18,013 --> 00:32:21,574
I am aware of your earlier vote.

394
00:32:22,717 --> 00:32:27,848
I am aware that it was unanimous.

395
00:32:30,192 --> 00:32:35,858
Nonetheless, I believe
we should restore the Springboks.

396
00:32:36,031 --> 00:32:38,829
[MURMURING]

397
00:32:39,634 --> 00:32:44,071
Restore their name, their emblem...

398
00:32:44,239 --> 00:32:46,764
...and their colors immediately.

399
00:32:49,978 --> 00:32:51,843
Let me tell you why.

400
00:32:53,014 --> 00:32:54,572
On Robben Island...

401
00:32:55,083 --> 00:33:01,283
...in Pollsmoor Prison,
all of my jailers were Afrikaners.

402
00:33:02,324 --> 00:33:04,053
For 27 years...

403
00:33:05,627 --> 00:33:07,857
...I studied them.

404
00:33:09,097 --> 00:33:11,827
I learned their language.

405
00:33:12,868 --> 00:33:15,132
Read their books...

406
00:33:16,037 --> 00:33:17,971
...their poetry.

407
00:33:19,074 --> 00:33:21,736
I had to know my enemy...

408
00:33:21,910 --> 00:33:24,606
...before I could prevail against him.

409
00:33:25,313 --> 00:33:29,340
And we did prevail, did we not?

410
00:33:29,584 --> 00:33:33,418
All of us here, we prevailed.

411
00:33:33,588 --> 00:33:37,319
Our enemy is no longer the Afrikaner.

412
00:33:38,660 --> 00:33:41,823
They are our fellow South Africans...

413
00:33:42,497 --> 00:33:46,763
...our partners in democracy.

414
00:33:47,435 --> 00:33:52,566
And they treasure Springbok rugby.

415
00:33:54,409 --> 00:33:58,675
If we take that away, we lose them.

416
00:33:59,981 --> 00:34:05,817
We prove that we are
what they feared we would be.

417
00:34:08,256 --> 00:34:10,486
We have to be better than that.

418
00:34:12,294 --> 00:34:15,127
We have to surprise them...

419
00:34:15,430 --> 00:34:17,523
...with the compassion...

420
00:34:18,300 --> 00:34:23,397
...with restraint and generosity.

421
00:34:24,472 --> 00:34:29,842
I know all of the things they denied us.

422
00:34:30,979 --> 00:34:36,918
But this is no time
to celebrate petty revenge.

423
00:34:37,686 --> 00:34:40,985
This is the time to build our nation...

424
00:34:41,156 --> 00:34:45,115
...using every single brick
available to us.

425
00:34:45,694 --> 00:34:49,130
Even if that brick comes wrapped
in green and gold.

426
00:34:53,468 --> 00:34:56,699
You elected me your leader.

427
00:34:58,039 --> 00:35:00,439
Let me lead you now.

428
00:35:02,043 --> 00:35:03,738
Who is with me on this?

429
00:35:07,315 --> 00:35:09,044
Who is with me?

430
00:35:23,498 --> 00:35:27,730
Twelve votes. Twelve.

431
00:35:27,902 --> 00:35:32,601
A luxury.
We only needed one more yes than no.

432
00:35:32,774 --> 00:35:35,834
What if you hadn't got it?

433
00:35:36,077 --> 00:35:40,173
Well, you know,
that is the party's decision.

434
00:35:40,348 --> 00:35:44,614
I'm sorry, Madiba, but we've got
problems everywhere we look.

435
00:35:44,786 --> 00:35:48,654
Housing, food, jobs, crime. Our currency.

436
00:35:48,823 --> 00:35:52,759
You can't keep interrupting
affairs of state to placate a minority.

437
00:35:52,927 --> 00:35:55,191
But I must.

438
00:35:55,363 --> 00:36:01,461
That minority still controls the police,
the army and the economy.

439
00:36:01,903 --> 00:36:05,600
If we lose them,
we cannot address the other issues.

440
00:36:06,474 --> 00:36:13,437
So this rugby
is just a political calculation?

441
00:36:15,517 --> 00:36:18,611
It is a human calculation.

442
00:36:19,587 --> 00:36:22,886
If we take away what they cherish...

443
00:36:23,058 --> 00:36:26,619
...the Springboks,
their national anthem...

444
00:36:26,795 --> 00:36:31,164
...we just reinforce
the cycle of fear between us.

445
00:36:32,634 --> 00:36:35,296
I will do what I must to stop that cycle.

446
00:36:37,238 --> 00:36:39,399
Or it will destroy us.

447
00:36:44,579 --> 00:36:47,639
ANNOUNCER:
- 42, South Africa, 20.

448
00:37:06,868 --> 00:37:09,234
Beer tastes like shit, man.

449
00:37:10,138 --> 00:37:12,265
It's not the beer.

450
00:37:14,676 --> 00:37:16,303
Take another.

451
00:37:16,478 --> 00:37:18,469
Everybody, take one.

452
00:37:21,483 --> 00:37:23,280
Pass them around.

453
00:37:28,456 --> 00:37:31,983
Right. I'd like to propose a toast.

454
00:37:32,994 --> 00:37:35,292
To the taste of defeat.

455
00:37:36,197 --> 00:37:37,630
Drink it.

456
00:37:37,799 --> 00:37:43,396
Remember this, and promise yourself
never to taste it again.

457
00:37:47,075 --> 00:37:49,566
You're right, it tastes like shit.

458
00:37:56,584 --> 00:38:00,076
Okay. Here's the schedule
for the overseas trip.

459
00:38:00,255 --> 00:38:02,018
Let me see.

460
00:38:09,531 --> 00:38:12,830
[SPEAKING IN AFRIKAANS]

461
00:38:13,001 --> 00:38:14,525
What did he just say?

462
00:38:14,702 --> 00:38:16,670
He asked when we were supposed
to sleep.

463
00:38:16,838 --> 00:38:20,535
- As well as other basic human functions.
JASON: Hey.

464
00:38:21,509 --> 00:38:25,036
If Madiba can do it, we can do it.

465
00:38:32,687 --> 00:38:35,747
In a common struggle...

466
00:38:35,924 --> 00:38:40,520
...that has brought
about our emancipation...

467
00:38:40,695 --> 00:38:45,598
...and pushed back
the frontier of racism...

468
00:38:46,334 --> 00:38:52,000
...the millions of our people
say thank you...

469
00:38:52,173 --> 00:38:54,198
...and thank you again.

470
00:38:54,542 --> 00:38:56,772
I come here with a message.

471
00:38:56,945 --> 00:39:00,642
People of the United States of America...

472
00:39:00,815 --> 00:39:06,583
... open your markets to us
and come invest in our country.

473
00:39:06,788 --> 00:39:09,951
MAN: And in Japan, President Mandela
met with Japanese officials...

474
00:39:10,124 --> 00:39:12,592
... as he concluded a grueling trip
to the Far East.

475
00:39:12,760 --> 00:39:15,752
And in related news, it was announced
that President Mandela...

476
00:39:15,930 --> 00:39:18,125
...will visit South Africa this week.

477
00:39:18,299 --> 00:39:19,960
[LAUGHING]

478
00:39:20,134 --> 00:39:22,364
Stop it, old man.

479
00:39:28,076 --> 00:39:30,067
Gee, it's cold, man.

480
00:39:41,689 --> 00:39:43,247
LINGA: Morning, Madiba.
- How are you?

481
00:39:43,424 --> 00:39:44,823
LINGA: Fine, thanks.
HENDRICK: Morning, sir.

482
00:39:45,460 --> 00:39:47,018
How is your family, Hendrick?

483
00:39:47,195 --> 00:39:50,028
Top shape, sir. How about yours?

484
00:39:53,034 --> 00:39:55,935
I have a very large family.

485
00:39:56,371 --> 00:39:58,771
Forty-two million.

486
00:40:03,411 --> 00:40:05,470
I don't think I'll walk today.

487
00:40:08,149 --> 00:40:11,585
- We never, never ask him about his family.
- But he asks about ours.

488
00:40:11,753 --> 00:40:15,086
Hey, think about it, man.
He's separated from his wife, his children.

489
00:40:15,256 --> 00:40:18,089
How often do you see them here, huh?

490
00:40:20,662 --> 00:40:23,790
He's not a saint, okay?
He's a man with a man's problems.

491
00:40:23,965 --> 00:40:26,957
He doesn't need us reminding him
about them.

492
00:40:36,377 --> 00:40:39,676
- Good morning, Madiba.
- Good morning.

493
00:40:40,014 --> 00:40:42,881
- Thank you very much.
- Enjoy it.

494
00:40:48,423 --> 00:40:50,414
Yes.

495
00:40:54,529 --> 00:40:56,326
Very good.

496
00:40:56,864 --> 00:40:58,923
Very good.

497
00:41:03,104 --> 00:41:05,664
- Ah, Brenda, good morning.
- Good morning, Madiba.

498
00:41:05,840 --> 00:41:09,037
- I like that dress.
- Thank you.

499
00:41:09,210 --> 00:41:12,509
- This is for you.
- What is it?

500
00:41:12,680 --> 00:41:15,774
Your paychecks.
You haven't been collecting them.

501
00:41:18,353 --> 00:41:21,550
- What's wrong?
- This is terrible.

502
00:41:21,723 --> 00:41:26,422
It's what de Klerk got,
plus an increase for inflation.

503
00:41:31,399 --> 00:41:34,266
Today President Mandela
announced that, in his opinion...

504
00:41:34,435 --> 00:41:36,528
- Thanks.
...his salary is too high.

505
00:41:36,704 --> 00:41:38,763
Dead right. They're all overpaid.

506
00:41:38,940 --> 00:41:43,877
He has, therefore, decided to donate
a third of his monthly income to charity.

507
00:41:44,712 --> 00:41:48,409
Give me the houses and cars they give him,
I'll donate a third of my salary too.

508
00:41:48,583 --> 00:41:51,143
- You would not, not in a million years.
- Pienaar. Hello.

509
00:41:51,819 --> 00:41:52,979
Hang on a moment, please.

510
00:41:53,154 --> 00:41:55,554
Mandela says that he wishes
to set an example...

511
00:41:55,723 --> 00:41:58,692
FRANGOIS: Yes. Of course.
...to other leaders and cabinet ministers.

512
00:41:59,460 --> 00:42:01,189
MANDELA: I thank you. Thank you.
- Fat chance.

513
00:42:01,362 --> 00:42:02,386
[MUTES TV]

514
00:42:02,563 --> 00:42:04,463
They're lining their pockets
as fast as they can.

515
00:42:04,632 --> 00:42:06,327
Must be his girlfriend, eh, Nerine?

516
00:42:06,501 --> 00:42:08,401
Oh, he knows I'll bloody well kill him.

517
00:42:08,569 --> 00:42:10,093
[MR. PIENAAR LAUGHS]

518
00:42:10,972 --> 00:42:12,303
NERINE:
What?

519
00:42:12,473 --> 00:42:13,963
Who was that?

520
00:42:14,142 --> 00:42:16,269
FRANGOIS: Well...
- I told you it was his girlfriend.

521
00:42:16,444 --> 00:42:17,843
Shh!

522
00:42:18,012 --> 00:42:19,843
I've been invited to tea.

523
00:42:20,314 --> 00:42:23,010
- With who?
- The president.

524
00:42:23,785 --> 00:42:25,446
President of SA Rugby?

525
00:42:25,620 --> 00:42:27,918
Count your fingers
after he shakes your hand, boy.

526
00:42:28,089 --> 00:42:29,852
The president.

527
00:42:34,195 --> 00:42:37,255
He wants me over for tea,
week after next.

528
00:42:39,200 --> 00:42:44,297
Mr. Frangois. You must tell Madiba
that the bus service is very bad...

529
00:42:44,472 --> 00:42:47,305
...and too expensive.
He must do something about it.

530
00:42:48,009 --> 00:42:50,876
- Good night, everybody.
MRS. PIENAAR: Good night, Eunice.

531
00:42:51,045 --> 00:42:52,478
Thank you.

532
00:42:52,814 --> 00:42:54,873
What the hell does he want with you?

533
00:42:57,985 --> 00:42:59,509
I don't know.

534
00:43:04,158 --> 00:43:06,854
Frangois, relax, you've met him before.

535
00:43:07,028 --> 00:43:09,963
- I shook his hand on the rugby field.
- And you didn't even vote.

536
00:43:10,798 --> 00:43:13,266
Come on, Nooks, he's still the president.

537
00:43:13,434 --> 00:43:15,629
I play rugby.
What am I gonna say to the guy?

538
00:43:15,803 --> 00:43:18,670
Say to him, "Thank you for inviting me."

539
00:43:19,507 --> 00:43:21,737
What if I pull something stupid
in front of him?

540
00:43:21,909 --> 00:43:25,538
You won't.
Okay, I'll pick you up right here.

541
00:43:27,748 --> 00:43:30,444
- Bye.
MAN 1: There's Frangois.

542
00:43:31,152 --> 00:43:34,417
- Frangois, picture, please.
MAN 2: Frangois, can we get picture?

543
00:43:34,589 --> 00:43:37,149
Yeah, okay. Over here, okay?

544
00:43:38,159 --> 00:43:42,027
FRANGOIS: How's it?
MAN 3: Can we have a comment?

545
00:43:53,875 --> 00:43:55,240
See who's coming for tea?

546
00:43:55,409 --> 00:43:57,536
Yeah, my nephew wanted me
to get his autograph.

547
00:43:57,712 --> 00:44:00,840
- Who?
- Frangois Pienaar.

548
00:44:01,015 --> 00:44:03,506
- Who wants to escort him in?
- I will.

549
00:44:03,684 --> 00:44:07,211
- Hey, no autographs, okay?
- I know how to do my job, okay?

550
00:44:08,890 --> 00:44:10,858
Who's this Frangois Pienaar?

551
00:44:11,025 --> 00:44:14,290
You can't be serious.
He's the captain of the Springboks.

552
00:44:15,029 --> 00:44:16,428
I like soccer, myself.

553
00:44:16,597 --> 00:44:18,497
Well, you know
what they say about soccer.

554
00:44:18,666 --> 00:44:20,896
It's a gentlemen's game
played by hooligans.

555
00:44:21,068 --> 00:44:24,526
On the other hand, rugby is
a hooligan's game played by gentlemen.

556
00:44:24,705 --> 00:44:28,607
Yeah, yeah, yeah, I've heard that one
before. It wasn't funny the first time.

557
00:44:30,945 --> 00:44:34,108
- Can I ask you a question, lieutenant?
- Yeah, of course.

558
00:44:34,415 --> 00:44:36,144
What's he like?

559
00:44:36,584 --> 00:44:39,917
When I worked for the previous president,
it was my job to be invisible.

560
00:44:40,087 --> 00:44:42,851
This president, well,
he found out I liked English toffee...

561
00:44:43,024 --> 00:44:45,993
...and he brought me some back
from his visit in England.

562
00:44:46,160 --> 00:44:48,355
To him, no one's invisible.

563
00:44:49,130 --> 00:44:52,566
That's where you wait.
One of his assistants will come for you.

564
00:44:52,733 --> 00:44:55,201
And the bathroom's over there
if you need it.

565
00:44:55,436 --> 00:44:57,631
Okay. Thanks.

566
00:44:59,640 --> 00:45:03,542
What are our chances in the World Cup?
I mean, for real.

567
00:45:05,079 --> 00:45:07,479
We'll do our best. That, I can guarantee.

568
00:45:11,953 --> 00:45:13,386
[PHONE RINGING]

569
00:45:13,554 --> 00:45:14,919
WOMAN:
Office of the president.

570
00:45:21,262 --> 00:45:22,923
So, what is he like?

571
00:45:23,097 --> 00:45:25,930
Well, he's not as big as he looks on TV.

572
00:45:26,100 --> 00:45:29,331
And we don't stand a bloody chance
in the World Cup.

573
00:45:34,475 --> 00:45:36,306
WOMAN:
Office of the president.

574
00:45:39,347 --> 00:45:42,748
Mr. Pienaar. Right this way, please.

575
00:45:42,917 --> 00:45:45,442
WOMAN:
Yeah. Thank you.

576
00:45:46,654 --> 00:45:48,281
Go on in.

577
00:45:49,323 --> 00:45:51,257
Frangois.

578
00:45:51,425 --> 00:45:53,655
What an honor.

579
00:45:53,828 --> 00:45:58,026
I am so excited. Thank you
for coming all this way to see me.

580
00:45:58,199 --> 00:46:00,724
Yes, sir. Thank you for inviting me,
Mr. President.

581
00:46:01,235 --> 00:46:03,897
So, tell me, Frangois, how is your ankle?

582
00:46:04,905 --> 00:46:09,842
- My ankle?
- I was told it was hurt. Has it healed?

583
00:46:11,045 --> 00:46:15,675
The truth is, sir, you never really play
at 100 percent, no matter what.

584
00:46:15,850 --> 00:46:19,047
Yes. In sports as in life, eh?

585
00:46:19,220 --> 00:46:21,085
- Yes, sir.
- Please, sit.

586
00:46:22,023 --> 00:46:25,322
Take this one.
Looking into the light hurts my eyes.

587
00:46:28,996 --> 00:46:33,956
Mrs. Brits.
You are a shining light in my day.

588
00:46:34,135 --> 00:46:35,932
Yes, sir.

589
00:46:36,103 --> 00:46:40,540
Mrs. Brits, this is Frangois Pienaar,
captain of the Springboks.

590
00:46:40,708 --> 00:46:43,268
[BOTH SPEAK IN AFRIKAANS]

591
00:46:44,045 --> 00:46:45,535
Shall I pour, sir?

592
00:46:45,713 --> 00:46:48,580
No, no. I would prefer to do it myself.

593
00:46:48,749 --> 00:46:51,582
Thank you very much, Mrs. Brits.

594
00:46:53,688 --> 00:46:56,156
How do you like your tea, Frangois?

595
00:46:56,324 --> 00:46:58,451
Just milk, please.

596
00:46:59,994 --> 00:47:02,963
MANDELA:
The English have given us many things...

597
00:47:03,130 --> 00:47:05,462
...including rugby.

598
00:47:05,866 --> 00:47:11,805
But afternoon tea, that is the greatest.

599
00:47:11,972 --> 00:47:13,906
There we are.

600
00:47:14,442 --> 00:47:15,534
Thank you, sir.

601
00:47:16,077 --> 00:47:19,205
You have a very difficult job.

602
00:47:19,580 --> 00:47:21,104
I do?

603
00:47:22,750 --> 00:47:24,240
I have a trading business.

604
00:47:24,418 --> 00:47:26,886
Captain of the Springboks.

605
00:47:27,621 --> 00:47:30,419
A very difficult job.

606
00:47:30,991 --> 00:47:32,891
Well, not compared to yours,
Mr. President.

607
00:47:33,060 --> 00:47:34,391
[MANDELA CHUCKLES]

608
00:47:34,562 --> 00:47:40,000
Well, no one is trying to tear my head off
while I'm doing mine.

609
00:47:40,167 --> 00:47:41,361
Yes, sir.

610
00:47:41,535 --> 00:47:43,799
Tell me, Frangois...

611
00:47:44,472 --> 00:47:47,498
...what is your philosophy on leadership?

612
00:47:47,675 --> 00:47:51,509
How do you inspire your team
to do their best?

613
00:47:52,813 --> 00:47:56,078
By example. I've always thought
to lead by example, sir.

614
00:47:56,250 --> 00:48:00,084
Well, that is right. That is exactly right.

615
00:48:00,254 --> 00:48:05,021
But how to get them to be better
than they think they can be?

616
00:48:05,192 --> 00:48:07,285
That is very difficult, I find.

617
00:48:08,462 --> 00:48:11,056
Inspiration, perhaps.

618
00:48:11,265 --> 00:48:16,100
How do we inspire ourselves to greatness,
when nothing less will do?

619
00:48:17,004 --> 00:48:20,838
How do we inspire everyone around us?

620
00:48:21,675 --> 00:48:25,270
I sometimes think it is
by using the work of others.

621
00:48:27,615 --> 00:48:29,810
On Robben Island...

622
00:48:30,384 --> 00:48:33,615
...when things got very bad...

623
00:48:34,455 --> 00:48:36,719
...I found inspiration in a poem.

624
00:48:37,458 --> 00:48:41,155
- A poem?
- A Victorian poem.

625
00:48:42,229 --> 00:48:44,129
Just words.

626
00:48:44,732 --> 00:48:50,898
But they helped me to stand
when all I wanted to do was to lie down.

627
00:48:53,207 --> 00:48:55,903
But you didn't come all this way
to hear an old man talk...

628
00:48:56,076 --> 00:48:57,703
...about things that make no sense.

629
00:48:57,878 --> 00:49:00,847
No, no, please, Mr. President.
It makes complete sense to me.

630
00:49:02,316 --> 00:49:06,218
On the day of a big match, say, a test...

631
00:49:06,387 --> 00:49:10,414
...in the bus on the way to the stadium,
nobody talks.

632
00:49:10,825 --> 00:49:15,319
- Yes. They're all preparing.
- Right.

633
00:49:15,496 --> 00:49:20,365
But when I think we're ready,
I have the bus driver put on a song.

634
00:49:20,534 --> 00:49:23,503
Something I've chosen, one we all know.

635
00:49:24,605 --> 00:49:27,199
And we listen to the words together.

636
00:49:28,542 --> 00:49:29,770
And it helps.

637
00:49:31,712 --> 00:49:38,675
I remember when I was invited to
the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona.

638
00:49:39,687 --> 00:49:44,351
Everybody in the stadium
greeted me with a song.

639
00:49:44,959 --> 00:49:47,553
At the time, the future...

640
00:49:47,728 --> 00:49:51,858
...our future, seemed very bleak.

641
00:49:52,600 --> 00:49:58,334
But to hear that song in the voices
of people from all over our planet...

642
00:49:58,506 --> 00:50:02,203
...made me proud to be South African.

643
00:50:02,543 --> 00:50:06,639
It inspired me to come home
and do better.

644
00:50:07,281 --> 00:50:11,217
It allowed me to expect more of myself.

645
00:50:11,886 --> 00:50:14,480
May I ask, what was the song, sir?

646
00:50:14,655 --> 00:50:19,592
Well, it was "Nkosi Sikelel' iAfrika."

647
00:50:20,794 --> 00:50:23,490
A very inspiring song.

648
00:50:24,832 --> 00:50:28,359
We need inspiration, Frangois.

649
00:50:28,802 --> 00:50:32,568
Because in order to build our nation...

650
00:50:32,806 --> 00:50:37,334
...we must all exceed
our own expectations.

651
00:50:51,492 --> 00:50:53,187
So, what's he like?

652
00:50:54,695 --> 00:50:57,789
He's not like anyone I've ever met before.

653
00:50:57,965 --> 00:51:00,695
Yeah, I hope. What did he want?

654
00:51:02,937 --> 00:51:06,737
What did he talk about? Did he talk
about rugby? What did he talk about?

655
00:51:07,341 --> 00:51:11,835
Frangois. It's like talking to a brick wall.
What did he say?

656
00:51:15,849 --> 00:51:18,841
I think he wants us to win the World Cup.

657
00:51:21,255 --> 00:51:25,157
[CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING]

658
00:51:31,365 --> 00:51:33,356
Excuse me.

659
00:51:45,646 --> 00:51:47,238
What do you think?

660
00:51:49,283 --> 00:51:52,878
- It doesn't matter what I think.
- Yes, it does.

661
00:51:53,854 --> 00:51:55,321
Okay.

662
00:51:55,489 --> 00:51:57,218
He looks like one of the policemen...

663
00:51:57,391 --> 00:52:00,383
...who forced us out of our house
when you were in jail.

664
00:52:00,794 --> 00:52:03,262
I don't like seeing you shake his hand...

665
00:52:03,430 --> 00:52:04,988
...and I'm not the only one.

666
00:52:09,203 --> 00:52:13,572
You criticize without understanding.

667
00:52:14,108 --> 00:52:17,407
You seek only to address
your own personal feelings.

668
00:52:18,612 --> 00:52:20,944
That is selfish thinking, Zindzi.

669
00:52:21,682 --> 00:52:23,912
It does not serve the nation.

670
00:52:27,921 --> 00:52:30,185
Zindzi, wait, please.

671
00:52:31,358 --> 00:52:33,383
Zindzi, l...

672
00:52:35,462 --> 00:52:36,986
Here.

673
00:52:40,234 --> 00:52:43,567
- Give this to your mother for me, please.
- What is it?

674
00:52:43,737 --> 00:52:46,763
It's a bracelet I found unpacking.

675
00:52:46,940 --> 00:52:48,805
Why don't you just throw it away?

676
00:52:50,010 --> 00:52:52,706
I don't have the right,
doesn't belong to me.

677
00:52:54,581 --> 00:52:57,948
If she left it, she meant to throw it away.

678
00:53:11,098 --> 00:53:13,464
Mrs. Pienaar said you were
finished with the paper.

679
00:53:13,634 --> 00:53:15,829
Yeah, yeah, of course.

680
00:53:19,606 --> 00:53:22,234
MAN 1: Let's go.
MAN 2: Go low. Yeah, that's it. Good boy.

681
00:53:23,444 --> 00:53:24,934
- There we go.
MAN 3: Hit.

682
00:53:25,679 --> 00:53:28,546
MINISTER: The World Cup is played
every four years.

683
00:53:28,716 --> 00:53:31,651
Sixteen teams qualify
from around the world.

684
00:53:31,819 --> 00:53:33,719
Four pools of four teams...

685
00:53:33,887 --> 00:53:37,448
...each playing in nine different venues
around the country.

686
00:53:37,624 --> 00:53:41,685
Two teams will advance from each pool
to the quarterfinals.

687
00:53:42,763 --> 00:53:47,257
Ivory Coast qualifies. That's wonderful.

688
00:53:47,434 --> 00:53:51,302
According to the experts,
we'll reach the quarterfinals and no further.

689
00:53:52,172 --> 00:53:56,973
According to the experts,
you and I should still be in jail.

690
00:54:00,380 --> 00:54:02,644
MINISTER: You make a personal appearance
at the finals...

691
00:54:02,816 --> 00:54:06,377
...and at the opening match
between Australia and the Springboks.

692
00:54:06,553 --> 00:54:11,889
The finals will be broadcast to over
a billion people around the world, live.

693
00:54:12,926 --> 00:54:15,121
A billion people watching us?

694
00:54:19,266 --> 00:54:22,258
This is a great opportunity.

695
00:54:27,074 --> 00:54:29,668
I reckon you've knocked
the stuffing out of them today.

696
00:54:29,843 --> 00:54:31,367
MAN 1: And now.
MAN 2: Come on, boys.

697
00:54:31,545 --> 00:54:33,672
I haven't even begun.

698
00:54:34,982 --> 00:54:38,042
We may not be the most talented team
in the world...

699
00:54:38,218 --> 00:54:41,085
...but we're sure as hell
going to be the fittest.

700
00:54:41,255 --> 00:54:42,279
Let's go again, guys.

701
00:54:42,456 --> 00:54:44,720
MAN 3: Come on, boys, nut up.
- Shit.

702
00:54:46,160 --> 00:54:48,025
- Brenda.
BRENDA: Yes, sir?

703
00:54:48,195 --> 00:54:50,925
Please get the head
of South African Rugby for me.

704
00:54:51,098 --> 00:54:53,362
- Right away.
- Thank you.

705
00:54:55,669 --> 00:54:57,694
Yep. One more.

706
00:55:02,876 --> 00:55:06,573
Guys, listen up.
Dr. Luyt just wants a few words, please.

707
00:55:09,550 --> 00:55:11,518
Afternoon, men.

708
00:55:11,685 --> 00:55:14,153
Good to see you all working so hard.

709
00:55:14,388 --> 00:55:16,413
I have a short announcement.

710
00:55:16,590 --> 00:55:19,388
As part of the PR buildup
to the World Cup...

711
00:55:19,560 --> 00:55:23,724
...you will be conducting coaching clinics
in townships all over the country.

712
00:55:23,897 --> 00:55:26,764
I know, I know.
You have plenty on your plates already.

713
00:55:26,934 --> 00:55:30,131
But this is a request from the top.

714
00:55:32,439 --> 00:55:34,339
The very top.

715
00:55:34,975 --> 00:55:36,670
Thank you.

716
00:55:43,483 --> 00:55:45,314
This is complete crap, man.

717
00:55:45,485 --> 00:55:48,147
What is this?
What are we, some sort of circus act now?

718
00:55:48,722 --> 00:55:52,089
We don't have time for shit like this.
They expect us to play our best...

719
00:55:52,259 --> 00:55:56,093
...to give our bloody all,
then they add to our bloody workload.

720
00:55:56,964 --> 00:55:59,398
What do you think about this, Chester?

721
00:56:00,734 --> 00:56:04,261
Well, I try not to think
because it interferes with my rugby.

722
00:56:04,805 --> 00:56:08,172
You see? Now, there's a rugby player.
Talk to them, cappie.

723
00:56:08,942 --> 00:56:11,206
Make them understand.
We don't have time for this.

724
00:56:11,378 --> 00:56:12,470
Yeah.

725
00:56:12,646 --> 00:56:14,546
- Yeah.
- I'm not going to talk to them.

726
00:56:14,715 --> 00:56:16,410
Why not?

727
00:56:17,050 --> 00:56:18,608
Okes...

728
00:56:18,785 --> 00:56:21,720
...we've become more
than just a rugby team...

729
00:56:21,889 --> 00:56:24,323
...and we might as well get used to it.

730
00:56:26,026 --> 00:56:30,087
- Is this you speaking or Mandela?
MAN: Yeah, exactly.

731
00:56:30,264 --> 00:56:32,255
You know me better than that.

732
00:56:37,838 --> 00:56:39,806
You know, times change.

733
00:56:42,142 --> 00:56:44,474
And we need to change as well.

734
00:57:20,914 --> 00:57:22,142
Shit.

735
00:57:22,316 --> 00:57:25,513
Yeah. Glad I don't live here, eh?

736
00:57:28,789 --> 00:57:30,620
Around there.

737
00:57:45,005 --> 00:57:47,997
Don't forget,
we've got cameras on us at all times.

738
00:57:48,175 --> 00:57:50,700
What a bloody joke.

739
00:57:50,877 --> 00:57:53,778
[CHILDREN CHEERING]

740
00:57:53,947 --> 00:57:57,178
CHILDREN [CHANTING]:
Chester! Chester! Chester!

741
00:58:10,998 --> 00:58:13,023
Chester, I reckon you're up.

742
00:58:13,200 --> 00:58:15,498
- What am I supposed to do?
- What you do best.

743
00:58:15,669 --> 00:58:17,330
Let rip.

744
00:58:17,938 --> 00:58:20,338
Who wants to play rugby?

745
00:58:34,187 --> 00:58:35,779
Who here knows the rules of rugby?

746
00:58:35,956 --> 00:58:37,082
- Me.
- What is it?

747
00:58:37,257 --> 00:58:39,248
You hit another player
when the ref is not looking.

748
00:58:39,426 --> 00:58:40,450
[MEN LAUGHING]

749
00:58:40,627 --> 00:58:42,458
No, no, no, the first rule of rugby...

750
00:58:42,629 --> 00:58:47,225
...is you can only pass the ball backwards
or sideways, all right? Shall we practice?

751
00:58:47,401 --> 00:58:49,733
BOY: Yes.
- All right. Form a line.

752
00:58:49,903 --> 00:58:50,927
Let's go, boys.

753
00:58:53,907 --> 00:58:56,000
Ready? Okay, pass.

754
00:58:58,311 --> 00:59:00,074
Keep your hands up.

755
00:59:04,885 --> 00:59:06,182
Yeah!

756
00:59:06,353 --> 00:59:10,119
Like this, like this. Pass it here.
I'm here and I'm running like this:

757
00:59:10,290 --> 00:59:11,655
I'm there.

758
00:59:11,825 --> 00:59:14,123
Now... Now... Now you run.

759
00:59:17,798 --> 00:59:19,459
There you go.

760
00:59:20,167 --> 00:59:23,625
And then catch it like that.
So I want you in groups of three, okay?

761
00:59:23,804 --> 00:59:26,102
All right, one, two, three.

762
00:59:28,141 --> 00:59:29,540
[YELLS]

763
00:59:29,709 --> 00:59:31,404
[LAUGHING]

764
00:59:57,971 --> 00:59:59,268
- Bokke!
- Yes!

765
00:59:59,439 --> 01:00:00,633
- Bokke!
- Yes!

766
01:00:00,807 --> 01:00:04,072
- Bokke!
- Yes, yes, yes!

767
01:00:14,621 --> 01:00:16,316
[HORN BEEPS]

768
01:00:16,490 --> 01:00:19,220
[CHILDREN CHEERING]

769
01:00:25,665 --> 01:00:28,498
And in addition
to the nationwide PR campaign...

770
01:00:28,668 --> 01:00:33,332
...we propose that all retail outlets
charge a nominal fee for plastic bags.

771
01:00:33,507 --> 01:00:36,271
- We believe that this will generate...
- Uh, excuse me.

772
01:00:37,043 --> 01:00:40,501
Mr. Minister, if you will forgive me,
this all sounds excellent...

773
01:00:40,680 --> 01:00:46,346
...and we will return to it, but if you
will indulge me for just one moment.

774
01:00:46,520 --> 01:00:49,751
MAN [ON TV]: Well, soccer is usually
their favorite sport here...

775
01:00:49,923 --> 01:00:54,792
... but things changed today when a group
of local kids really took to the Springboks...

776
01:00:54,961 --> 01:00:56,792
... in a surprise visit
where Frangois Pienaar...

777
01:00:56,963 --> 01:00:58,396
[CHUCKLES]

778
01:00:58,565 --> 01:01:04,299
You see that? That picture
is worth any number of speeches.

779
01:01:05,272 --> 01:01:09,709
This is part of President Mandela's
"one team, one country" campaign.

780
01:01:26,560 --> 01:01:30,326
This is Johan de Villiers
reporting live from Cape Town Airport...

781
01:01:30,497 --> 01:01:32,590
...where the Springbok flight
has just landed.

782
01:01:32,766 --> 01:01:34,529
- Thank you.
DE VILLIERS: The green and gold...

783
01:01:34,701 --> 01:01:35,895
...have just one week...

784
01:01:36,069 --> 01:01:38,833
...to put the finishing touches
to their grueling training program.

785
01:01:39,005 --> 01:01:43,271
And I, for one, must admit
to being cautiously optimistic.

786
01:01:43,443 --> 01:01:47,903
I say "cautiously"
because in my humble opinion...

787
01:01:48,081 --> 01:01:52,313
...this Springbok team
has been over-practiced on the field...

788
01:01:52,485 --> 01:01:54,715
...and overcommitted off it...

789
01:01:54,888 --> 01:01:59,484
...which makes beating a powerhouse
Australian side in next week's Cup opener...

790
01:01:59,659 --> 01:02:03,459
... a tall order, especially as this is
an inexperienced team...

791
01:02:03,630 --> 01:02:06,929
... with a history of coming up short
in big matches.

792
01:02:07,100 --> 01:02:09,227
This is Johan de Villiers,
live in Cape Town...

793
01:02:09,402 --> 01:02:12,132
... returning you to the studio
in Johannesburg.

794
01:02:12,439 --> 01:02:17,035
MAN: Thanks, Johan, for the update...
- Around the world, objectively...

795
01:02:17,277 --> 01:02:20,542
...what are they saying
about our chances to beat Australia?

796
01:02:20,714 --> 01:02:23,683
Everyone thinks they'll beat us,
and if they do...

797
01:02:23,850 --> 01:02:28,514
...we'll have to go through England
and the All Blacks just to get to the final.

798
01:02:28,688 --> 01:02:33,591
So it is very important
that we beat Australia?

799
01:02:35,195 --> 01:02:36,822
Thank you.

800
01:02:48,475 --> 01:02:53,708
Madiba? The cabinet ministers are here
to brief you on the trip to Taiwan.

801
01:02:53,880 --> 01:02:55,677
Oh, yes. I'll be right out.

802
01:02:55,849 --> 01:02:57,441
Thank you, sir.

803
01:03:41,695 --> 01:03:43,822
One week, boys.

804
01:03:53,340 --> 01:03:57,470
We want snipers on top of the stadium
and the surrounding buildings here.

805
01:03:57,644 --> 01:03:58,872
No problem.

806
01:03:59,045 --> 01:04:01,912
We want those two approaches
completely sanitized.

807
01:04:02,082 --> 01:04:03,106
Two approaches?

808
01:04:03,283 --> 01:04:06,844
We're not gonna decide which way
he comes in until the very last moment.

809
01:04:07,020 --> 01:04:12,117
We want uniforms, plain-clothes,
sharpshooters.

810
01:04:12,292 --> 01:04:13,486
And sniffer dogs.

811
01:04:13,660 --> 01:04:17,152
If you need more men, we have an
army unit for you on standby at Silvermine.

812
01:04:17,831 --> 01:04:20,561
We're not going to
take chances, gentlemen.

813
01:04:20,734 --> 01:04:23,259
The president is going to be exposed.

814
01:04:24,037 --> 01:04:26,232
Much too exposed.

815
01:04:36,616 --> 01:04:38,311
Brenda...

816
01:04:39,519 --> 01:04:41,544
...I have been studying.

817
01:04:41,721 --> 01:04:45,088
For the summit in Taiwan? Good.

818
01:04:45,258 --> 01:04:48,091
No. Not exactly.

819
01:04:48,261 --> 01:04:49,922
Test me.

820
01:04:50,163 --> 01:04:53,030
They look like thugs.

821
01:04:53,199 --> 01:04:58,034
Block out their names.
See if I can recognize them.

822
01:05:02,409 --> 01:05:05,674
Andr Joubert. Gavin Johnson.

823
01:05:06,880 --> 01:05:08,370
Did I get them right?

824
01:05:08,548 --> 01:05:10,539
Yes, Madiba.

825
01:05:10,950 --> 01:05:14,351
That's the way I used to study
in law school.

826
01:05:14,687 --> 01:05:19,784
Unfortunately, Chester is far too easy
to identify.

827
01:05:19,959 --> 01:05:24,623
But that will change. It must.

828
01:05:37,977 --> 01:05:39,342
FRANGOIS:
Team meeting after dinner.

829
01:05:39,512 --> 01:05:41,036
WOMAN:
Frangois!

830
01:05:41,214 --> 01:05:43,808
MAN:
Good luck, Springboks!

831
01:05:53,393 --> 01:05:55,293
All right, gather around.

832
01:05:57,263 --> 01:05:59,163
- Pass them around.
- What's this, homework?

833
01:05:59,332 --> 01:06:00,629
FRANGOIS:
Yeah, yeah. A little.

834
01:06:00,800 --> 01:06:02,927
Make sure everyone's got one.

835
01:06:05,271 --> 01:06:06,295
What is this?

836
01:06:06,473 --> 01:06:09,840
Right. We need to learn this song.
We can't just mouth the words anymore.

837
01:06:10,009 --> 01:06:12,307
Nobody cares as long as
we're winning the matches.

838
01:06:12,479 --> 01:06:14,344
You're wrong, they do care.

839
01:06:14,514 --> 01:06:16,709
It's their bloody song, not ours.

840
01:06:16,883 --> 01:06:20,614
- Flipping terrorist song, man.
- They used to arrest you for singing it.

841
01:06:20,787 --> 01:06:22,618
Right, and now it's one of our anthems.

842
01:06:22,789 --> 01:06:25,883
I can't even read it
or pronounce the words.

843
01:06:28,261 --> 01:06:31,628
All right, okes, it's optional.
Take it if you want to.

844
01:06:39,839 --> 01:06:42,034
It means "God Bless Africa."

845
01:06:44,577 --> 01:06:47,375
Which, you have to admit, we could use.

846
01:06:59,794 --> 01:07:04,993
Tell us, Mr. President,
have you always been a rugby fan?

847
01:07:05,633 --> 01:07:10,536
People don't realize
that I played rugby myself...

848
01:07:10,705 --> 01:07:13,697
...when I was a student at Fort Hare.

849
01:07:13,875 --> 01:07:17,868
It is a very rough game,
almost as rough as politics.

850
01:07:20,014 --> 01:07:22,448
How do you think the Springboks
will do?

851
01:07:22,617 --> 01:07:24,983
Oh, I think they will do very well.

852
01:07:25,153 --> 01:07:27,917
Their level of commitment is tremendous.

853
01:07:28,356 --> 01:07:32,315
Now, it's been said
that you used to support any team...

854
01:07:32,493 --> 01:07:34,461
...that played against the Springboks.

855
01:07:34,629 --> 01:07:37,655
Yes, well,
obviously that is no longer true.

856
01:07:37,832 --> 01:07:40,858
I am 100 percent behind our boys.

857
01:07:41,035 --> 01:07:46,200
After all, if I cannot change
when circumstances demand it...

858
01:07:46,374 --> 01:07:49,275
...how can I expect others to?

859
01:08:42,296 --> 01:08:44,196
- Frangois.
- Welcome, Mr. President.

860
01:08:44,365 --> 01:08:45,992
Gentlemen.

861
01:08:46,167 --> 01:08:50,831
Forgive me for interrupting your work
the day before such an important match.

862
01:08:51,506 --> 01:08:56,466
But I just wanted to come
and wish you good luck in person.

863
01:08:56,644 --> 01:09:03,072
Sometimes, very seldom, as president,
I am allowed to do what I want.

864
01:09:03,851 --> 01:09:08,185
- Mr. President. This is...
- Oh, I know who this is.

865
01:09:08,356 --> 01:09:10,916
- Andr. Good luck.
- Pleased to meet you. Thank you, sir.

866
01:09:11,092 --> 01:09:13,583
- Brendan. Good luck to you.
- Mr. President.

867
01:09:13,761 --> 01:09:15,194
- Gavin.
- Mr. President.

868
01:09:15,363 --> 01:09:17,422
- Good luck. James.
- Mr. President.

869
01:09:17,598 --> 01:09:18,622
- Good luck.
- Thank you.

870
01:09:18,800 --> 01:09:20,131
- Japie.
- Thanks, sir.

871
01:09:20,301 --> 01:09:21,495
Good luck.

872
01:09:21,669 --> 01:09:24,604
- Did you ever imagine this?
MANDELA: Good luck.

873
01:09:24,772 --> 01:09:26,239
How could I?

874
01:09:26,407 --> 01:09:28,875
- It's an honor, sir.
- Thank you. Good luck.

875
01:09:29,043 --> 01:09:30,271
- Mr. President.
- Good luck.

876
01:09:30,445 --> 01:09:31,742
Thank you.

877
01:09:31,913 --> 01:09:33,505
- Good luck to you.
- Thank you, sir.

878
01:09:33,681 --> 01:09:35,080
- Sir.
- Good luck.

879
01:09:35,650 --> 01:09:37,379
- Sir.
- Good luck, son.

880
01:09:37,552 --> 01:09:38,712
Good luck.

881
01:09:38,886 --> 01:09:40,581
- Hennie, good luck.
- Sir.

882
01:09:40,755 --> 01:09:42,154
But...

883
01:09:43,725 --> 01:09:44,885
...where is Chester?

884
01:09:47,095 --> 01:09:48,426
- He's injured, sir.
- Hm?

885
01:09:48,596 --> 01:09:51,997
His hamstring.
We're trying to keep it quiet.

886
01:09:52,500 --> 01:09:56,027
Well, will he be out
for the entire tournament?

887
01:09:57,505 --> 01:10:00,406
With hamstrings, who knows?

888
01:10:01,008 --> 01:10:02,032
We'll miss him.

889
01:10:02,977 --> 01:10:05,411
The whole country will miss him.

890
01:10:06,447 --> 01:10:08,278
- Well, gentlemen...
- Mr. President, sir.

891
01:10:08,449 --> 01:10:11,782
- Yes, Hennie?
- This is for you from us.

892
01:10:17,759 --> 01:10:20,159
I am honored, gentlemen.

893
01:10:20,328 --> 01:10:22,057
Truly honored.

894
01:10:22,530 --> 01:10:25,158
And you must know that...

895
01:10:25,600 --> 01:10:29,058
...your country supports you completely.

896
01:10:29,604 --> 01:10:31,094
Good luck to you all.

897
01:10:31,272 --> 01:10:33,638
- Thank you, sir.
- Frangois, walk with me.

898
01:10:37,211 --> 01:10:39,975
I have something for you.

899
01:10:43,117 --> 01:10:45,881
It has helped me through the years.

900
01:10:46,053 --> 01:10:48,283
I hope it helps you.

901
01:10:48,790 --> 01:10:50,121
Thank you, Mr. President.

902
01:10:50,758 --> 01:10:52,248
Thank you.

903
01:11:03,704 --> 01:11:06,571
MARY:
It's time for bed, Dada.

904
01:11:07,341 --> 01:11:11,300
I'm going to stay up a while.
The country is excited tonight.

905
01:11:11,479 --> 01:11:13,606
You need to sleep, the doctor said.

906
01:11:15,349 --> 01:11:18,443
The doctor has no sense of occasion.

907
01:11:20,755 --> 01:11:22,780
MAN: A good clearance
from the base of the scrum.

908
01:11:25,393 --> 01:11:26,553
A good result here today.

909
01:11:26,727 --> 01:11:29,662
It's perfect conditions
in front of a full house.

910
01:11:31,165 --> 01:11:34,464
Strong tackle. Nice offload.

911
01:11:49,317 --> 01:11:52,184
[KNOCKING]

912
01:11:57,859 --> 01:11:59,053
Hello.

913
01:11:59,227 --> 01:12:01,092
- Thank you.
- Thank you, sir.

914
01:12:01,262 --> 01:12:04,322
You know what's the best thing
about you being the captain?

915
01:12:04,899 --> 01:12:06,366
- The honor?
- No.

916
01:12:06,534 --> 01:12:09,128
You don't have to share a room.

917
01:12:09,303 --> 01:12:12,431
- No, no, no. I can't, I can't.
- Come on, Frangois, it's been weeks.

918
01:12:12,607 --> 01:12:15,940
I need to be angry. I know, it's working.
I need to be angry tomorrow.

919
01:12:16,110 --> 01:12:17,304
What's this?

920
01:12:17,478 --> 01:12:19,878
A poem from the president.

921
01:12:20,047 --> 01:12:22,379
How does a poem help you play rugby?

922
01:12:22,550 --> 01:12:26,213
The same way your visit does.
Inspiration.

923
01:12:37,064 --> 01:12:39,362
[GRUNTING]

924
01:12:39,533 --> 01:12:41,160
MAN:
Here we go!

925
01:12:48,809 --> 01:12:50,709
Heads up! Heads up!

926
01:13:10,965 --> 01:13:13,263
- What happened?
- We scored.

927
01:13:21,175 --> 01:13:22,802
MAN:
Come on!

928
01:13:42,063 --> 01:13:43,758
ANNOUNCER:
Try, Australia.

929
01:13:46,634 --> 01:13:48,602
[GRUNTING]

930
01:13:55,643 --> 01:13:57,508
Yes.

931
01:13:57,678 --> 01:13:59,168
Number 10, Stransky.

932
01:14:12,560 --> 01:14:14,323
Yes! Yes!

933
01:14:14,495 --> 01:14:17,760
- We won.
- We did?

934
01:14:17,932 --> 01:14:19,923
Good, Dada.

935
01:14:43,190 --> 01:14:45,488
- Very good.
- It's beautiful, Dada.

936
01:14:45,659 --> 01:14:48,457
- Well, then, what do you say now?
- Well, that was fantastic.

937
01:14:54,668 --> 01:14:57,501
[VIOLINS PLAYING]

938
01:15:09,650 --> 01:15:11,880
You must be very happy.

939
01:15:12,053 --> 01:15:16,012
Any man would be happy dancing
with a beautiful lady like you.

940
01:15:17,124 --> 01:15:21,322
- Mr. President, you're exaggerating.
- Not at all.

941
01:15:21,495 --> 01:15:25,659
My father was Xhosa,
so he was a polygamist.

942
01:15:26,400 --> 01:15:28,391
As you know, I am not.

943
01:15:29,837 --> 01:15:33,603
But when I look at you, I envy my father.

944
01:15:33,774 --> 01:15:36,470
[LAUGHING]

945
01:16:02,103 --> 01:16:06,267
MEN [SINGING]:
Here's to Joel, he's so blue

946
01:16:06,440 --> 01:16:10,035
He's a drunkard through and through

947
01:16:10,211 --> 01:16:13,305
He's a bastard, so they say

948
01:16:13,481 --> 01:16:16,382
He tried to go to heaven
But he went the other way

949
01:16:16,550 --> 01:16:21,146
Say one, two, three, four, hey!

950
01:16:26,694 --> 01:16:28,719
Coach's run, 6 a.m.

951
01:16:28,896 --> 01:16:31,592
- What?
- Pass it on.

952
01:16:33,134 --> 01:16:36,035
- Coach's run, 6 a.m.
MAN: You gotta be kidding me.

953
01:16:36,203 --> 01:16:39,798
- Six. Drink up.
- Nothing more for you then.

954
01:16:39,974 --> 01:16:44,343
Joel, coach's run, 6. Six a.m.

955
01:17:21,749 --> 01:17:24,547
Hey, guys. I hope you're
not going to be this slow next week.

956
01:17:25,586 --> 01:17:27,918
- Hi, Nooks.
- Cappie, what's going on?

957
01:17:28,088 --> 01:17:30,147
- A change of pace. Come.
- You sneaky bugger.

958
01:17:30,324 --> 01:17:33,487
FRANGOIS:
Here you go. Come on, guys. Come.

959
01:17:55,216 --> 01:17:58,379
[HORN BLOWS]

960
01:18:18,839 --> 01:18:21,000
They used to smuggle gravel
in from the yard...

961
01:18:21,175 --> 01:18:23,871
...throw it across the floor.
They could hear the wardens coming.

962
01:18:24,044 --> 01:18:26,035
Oh, wow.

963
01:18:27,181 --> 01:18:30,446
- Can we see the president's cell?
- Yes. Yes, of course.

964
01:18:31,552 --> 01:18:34,077
Lord, can you believe this?

965
01:18:35,923 --> 01:18:39,154
Now, the number on the door, 46664...

966
01:18:39,326 --> 01:18:44,628
...means he was the 466th prisoner
to be interned here in 1964.

967
01:18:45,132 --> 01:18:47,862
We've done it up just the way it was.

968
01:18:55,209 --> 01:18:56,233
Come with me.

969
01:19:34,815 --> 01:19:37,306
MANDELA [IN VOICE-OVER]:
Out of the night that covers me

970
01:19:38,285 --> 01:19:41,015
Black as the Pit from pole to pole

971
01:19:42,089 --> 01:19:45,456
I thank whatever gods may be

972
01:19:45,859 --> 01:19:48,157
For my unconquerable soul.

973
01:19:49,363 --> 01:19:51,957
In the fell clutch of circumstance

974
01:19:53,600 --> 01:19:57,593
I have not winced nor cried aloud.

975
01:19:57,900 --> 01:20:00,198
Under the bludgeonings of fate

976
01:20:01,103 --> 01:20:05,005
